<v Maya>So they are synthesizing hardware knowledge with live AI software.</v>

156
00:17:21.306 --> 00:17:22.066
<v Daniel>Yes, exactly. They</v>

157
00:17:22.106 --> 00:17:33.255
<v Maya>develop quick fix rules, like if the altimeter is noisy but the GPS is steady, it is a barometric sensor failure. Or, you know, if wind gusts hit 15 miles per hour, tell the AI to slow the descent rate by 10%.</v>

158
00:17:33.555 --> 00:17:48.133
<v Daniel>If we connect this to the bigger picture, this highlights the vital transition we must make. We must move away from teaching students to be repetitive answer tools. AI is infinitely better at repetitive calculation than a human will ever be.</v>

159
00:17:49.094 --> 00:18:01.618
<v Daniel>Instead, we have to teach iterative cycles of doing, receiving feedback, reflecting, and heuristic abstraction. The AI simply becomes a dashboard for strategic problem solving.</v>

160
00:18:01.947 --> 00:18:07.829
<v Maya>It really is a complete inversion of how we think about a physics education. I mean, we've traced this incredible arc today. We</v>

161
00:18:07.889 --> 00:18:08.369
<v Daniel>really have.</v>

162
00:18:08.509 --> 00:18:23.155
<v Maya>We started with a 2023 version of ChatGPT that functioned like an overconfident student fumbling basic algebra. Fast forward just two years, and we were looking at reasoning models that crushed the physics Olympiad, grade complex written reasoning with human level accuracy.</v>

163
00:18:23.795 --> 00:18:25.916
<v Maya>and act as real-time Socratic tutors.</v>

164
00:18:25.996 --> 00:18:36.762
<v Daniel>And beyond the classroom, we see autoencoders filtering LHC noise, geometric neural networks intrinsically respecting 3D physical symmetries, and reinforcement learning actively containing nuclear fusion.</v>

165
00:18:36.842 --> 00:18:37.743
<v Maya>It's just wild.</v>

166
00:18:37.903 --> 00:18:42.005
<v Daniel>The technology has matured from a text predictor to fundamental scientific infrastructure.</v>

167
00:18:42.445 --> 00:18:57.404
<v Maya>So, to the faculty sitting at the AAPT workshop today, you are the architects of this transition. Incorporating data science and AI does not detract from core physics. It amplifies it. Absolutely. It gives your students the computational leverage they need</v>

168
00:18:57.444 --> 00:19:04.490
<v Maya>to actually participate in modern research. And through communities like DSA Cop, you don't have to build these modules from scratch.</v>

169
00:19:04.590 --> 00:19:15.339
<v Daniel>No. The lesson plans, the code, the workflows, they are being built collaboratively right now by your peers. It is an unprecedented opportunity to redefine the undergraduate experience.</v>

170
00:19:15.600 --> 00:19:19.224
<v Maya>But it also leaves us with a pretty profound question to wrestle with as we close out.</v>

171
00:19:19.344 --> 00:19:19.925
<v Daniel>Oh, definitely.</v>

172
00:19:20.065 --> 00:19:34.761
<v Maya>If AI systems are increasingly capable of perfectly simulating physical environments, formulating mathematical hypotheses, analyzing the resulting data, and even grading the tests, what does a human physics degree actually certify by the end of this</v>

173
00:19:34.801 --> 00:19:48.556
<v Maya>decade? heavy thought. If we are outsourcing the calculation and the simulation, will the most valuable skill for a human physicist of the 2030s simply be the philosophical intuition of knowing which scientific questions are actually worth asking in the first place?</v>

174
00:19:48.896 --> 00:19:56.062
<v Daniel>I think so. In a world of infinite answers, knowing how to ask the right question becomes the ultimate human advantage.</v>

175
00:19:56.862 --> 00:20:02.747
<v Maya>Something to think about as you head into your next session. That's all for this deep dive. Thanks for listening and enjoy the rest of your workshop.</v>
